Key Findings

  • Surveyed 84 sites across 10 rivers
  • Detected 29,868 ESVs representing 1,903 species and 519 families
  • Found 4 conservation priority species: Water vole, Eurasian otter, Water shrew, Great crested newt
  • Detected 3 invasive species requiring management attention
  • Most biodiverse rivers: Beane, Misbourne, Upper Lea

2. Methods Overview

ðŸ§ª Sampling

Water samples were collected from chalk stream sites across the study area. At each site, water was filtered through 0.45Î¼m filters to capture environmental DNA. Multiple filters were collected at some sites to assess sampling variability.

ðŸ”¬ Laboratory

DNA was extracted from filters and amplified using metabarcoding primers targeting invertebrate communities. PCR products were sequenced on Illumina platforms to generate paired-end reads.

ðŸ’» Bioinformatics

Sequences were processed to generate Exact Sequence Variants (ESVs) - unique DNA sequences representing distinct taxonomic units. ESVs were assigned taxonomy using reference databases (BOLD, MIDORI) with similarity thresholds for species-level identification.

ðŸ“Š Analysis

Biodiversity metrics were calculated including ESV richness, species counts, and EPT (Ephemeroptera, Plecoptera, Trichoptera) indices. Community similarity was assessed using Jaccard indices. Indicator species analysis identified taxa characteristic of specific rivers.

6. Conservation Recommendations

Monitoring

  • Continue eDNA monitoring at established sites to track biodiversity trends over time
  • Prioritise sites with high EPT diversity for ongoing water quality assessment
  • Consider seasonal sampling to capture temporal variation in communities

Habitat Management

  • Protect and enhance riparian habitats, particularly at high-diversity sites
  • Address any identified pollution sources affecting sensitive taxa
  • Support river restoration projects that benefit invertebrate communities

Invasive Species

  • Implement biosecurity measures at sites where invasive species were detected
  • Consider targeted removal or control programmes where feasible
  • Monitor spread of invasive species to new sites

Data Sharing

  • Share findings with local Rivers Trusts and conservation organisations
  • Contribute species records to national biodiversity databases
  • Engage citizen scientists in ongoing monitoring efforts
